@node Introduction "mrjQuote : Introduction"
@{par}@{b}Introduction to mrjQuote@{ub}
@{par}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{par}  In the beginning, this was a simple program with the sole purpose of popping
up a random quote from Babylon 5. Since then it has suffered the effects of
creeping featurism and has evolved into what I hope is a much more useful,
multipurpose quote generation utility.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Features:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par} @{"  " link Usage} Can produce quotes in a requester or direct to the CLI
@{par} @{"  " link Sigs} Flexible random signature generation
@{par} @{"  " link More} Powerful QuoteList format allowing access to multiple files
@{par} @{"  " link Configuration} Font-sensitive configuration window
@{par} @{"  " link Commodity} Access to basic features via hotkeys and the commodities exchange
@{par} @{"  " link ARexx} Extensive ARexx support with example scripts
@{par} @{"  " link Babylon5} Ready to use with hundreds of quotes from Babylon 5
@{par}
@endnode
@node Usage "mrjQuote : Usage"
@{par}@{b}Usage@{ub}
@{par}~~~~~
@{par}@{b}From CLI/Shell:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}Quote [<QuoteList>] [SIG [<SigList>]] [REQ] [CDITY] [AREXX] [QUIET]
@{par}
@{par}@{b}SIG:  @{ub} Generate a signature instead of a quote
@{par}@{b}REQ:  @{ub} Force requester output rather than to CLI
@{par}@{b}CDITY:@{ub} @{"Install mrjQuote as a commodity" link Commodity} (implies REQ if succesful)
@{par}@{b}AREXX:@{ub} @{"Give mrjQuote an ARexx port" link ARexx} (implies REQ if succesful)
@{par}@{b}QUIET:@{ub} Do not produce any output on startup
@{par}
@{par}  QuoteLists and SigLists must be supplied with full path, and should be
before or after the SIG keyword as shown above. If CDITY or AREXX is given,
you may wish to 'Run Quote ...' as otherwise the CLI will be hung.
@{par}  Alternatively, you can use the ARexx script @{"mrjQuote.rexx" link Rexx} which will
utilise the ARexx port of an already-running copy of mrjQuote, only loading
the program if neccessary.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}From Workbench:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}  Double click on icon. You can also shift-double-click on a QuoteFile, or set
mrjQuote as the default tool in the icon of a Quote file. Starting from
Workbench is equivalent to using the switches REQ CDITY AREXX from the CLI.
@{par}  If you're running Directory Opus 5.5, there's an ARexx module
@{"mrjQuote.dopus5" link DOpus5}, which can load mrjQuote as required and provide acess to it
via internal Directory Opus commands.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}The requester buttons have the following purpose:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}OK:     @{ub} Closes the requester, but leaves mrjQuote running.
@{par}                   (Only available if CDITY or AREXX given)
@{par}@{b}Quit:   @{ub} Exits the program completely.
@{par}@{b}Another:@{ub} Pops up a new quote.
@{par}
@{par}  The flexible @{"QuoteList format" link More} allows you to reference several smaller files
by having instead of a file full of quotes a file  containing a list of files,
one of which will be chosen at random (and which itself may be either full of
quotes or links to other files.
@{par}  If a Quotelist/SigList is not supplied from the CLI or Workbench, then the
files set in the @{"configuration" link Configuration} will be used. By
default, this is PROGDIR:QuoteList and PROGDIR:SigList.
@{par}
@endnode
@node Sigs "mrjQuote : Random Signatures"
@{par}@{b}Random Signatures@{ub}
@{par}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{par}  To cater for the ever-increasing number of Amiga owners who use their
machine to access the Internet, mrjQuote now provides a facility to generate
random signature files for appending to emails or news articles. As well as a
random quote, you can specify files which may be attatched to the beginning
and/or end of every signature, perhaps giving your email address and web page
URL. Remember however that netiquette suggests that signatures should be
limited to four lines. A special selection of one/two line @{"Babylon 5" link Babylon5} quotes
has been included for this purpose. Don't to forget to include an ASCII
jumpgate <*> the internet symbol of Babylon 5 fandom (unless, of course,
you're not a B5 fan - in which case, why not?).
@{par}  You can generate a signature file either by pressing the appropriate button
in the @{"configuration window" link Configuration} or, more conveniently, via a @{"commodities hotkey" link Commodity}.
You can also do so via the @{"ARexx port" link ARexx} - perhaps automatically from your mail
or news program or @{"text editor" link Editor}.
@{par}
@endnode
@node Configuration "mrjQuote : The Configuration Window"
@{par}@{b}Configuration@{ub}
@{par}~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{par}  Under Workbench 2 or above, mrjQuote has its own configuration window. The
window can be opened via the @{"Commodities" link Commodity} Exchange, a hotkey, or an
{"ARexx" link ARexx} message. On opening the window, the current settings will be saved in
the file T:mrjQuote.prefs for use with Cancel.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Gadgets:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}@{" GUI  Font " link A_font} [ Current.font / Size  ]  [ .signature File      ] @{" .sig file " link A_sfile}
@{par}@{" QuoteList " link A_qlist} [ QuoteList            ]  [ SigList              ] @{"  SigList  " link A_slist}
@{par}@{"   Quote   " link A_quote} [ Quote HotKey         ]  [ Signature HotKey     ] @{" Signature " link A_sig}
@{par}@{" Configure " link A_open} [ Configuration HotKey ]  [ Signature Pre File   ] @{" .sig  pre " link A_spre}
@{par}@{" Rexx Name " link A_macro} [ ARexx Port Name      ]  [ Signature Post File  ] @{" .sig post " link A_spost}
@{par}@{"   Save    " link A_save} @{"  Save As  " link A_saveas} @{"    Use    " link A_use} @{"   Load    " link A_load} @{"  Cancel   " link A_cancel} @{"   Quit    " link A_quit}
@{par}
@{par}  The three hotkeys and port name can be changed by editing them directly in
their string gadget (note that changes will not be seen unless you press enter
or refresh the configuration window). The ARexx port name cannot be changed
interactively, but if saved will be used next time you load mrjQuote. You
shouldn't really change it unless you have a very good reason, as most ARexx
scripts will also need altering. The filenames and font name can be clicking
on the adjacent button to pop up a standard file or font requester. If one of
the letters in a button is underlined then Right-Amiga plus that letter is a
keyboard shortcut to that function.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Menus:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Project Menu:@{ub}     @{" About     " link A_about} Right-Amiga A
@{par}                  @{" Quote     " link A_quote} Right-Amiga O
@{par}                  @{" Signature " link A_sig} Right-Amiga I
@{par}                  @{" Macro     " link A_macro} Right-Amiga M
@{par}                  @{" Quit      " link A_quit} Right-Amiga Q
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Preferences Menu:@{ub} @{" Use       " link A_use} Right-Amiga U
@{par}                  @{" Save      " link A_save} Right-Amiga S
@{par}                  @{" Save As   " link A_saveas} Right-Amiga V
@{par}                  @{" Load      " link A_load} Right-Amiga L
@{par}                  @{" Cancel    " link A_cancel} Right-Amiga C
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Setting the Message of the Day:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}  mrjQuote has the ability to insert a text file at the top of the first quote
produced in a requester after a reboot. You could, perhaps, use this to give
your name and address in case your beloved Amiga should 'stray'. To enable
this facility, simply create a file ENVARC:mrjsq/MOTD containing the required
text.
@{par}
@endnode
@node Commodity "mrjQuote : Use as a Commodity"
@{par}@{b}Use as a Commodity@{ub}
@{par}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{par}  Under Workbench 2 or above, mrjQuote can install itself as a commodity. This
allows you to control some aspects of the program via hotkeys and the
commodities exchange.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Default Hotkeys:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}(these can be changed from the @{"configuration window" link Configuration})
@{par}
@{par}@{" Pop up a quote       " link A_quote} left-alt control Q
@{par}@{" Configuration window " link A_open} right-alt control Q
@{par}@{" Generate a signature " link A_sig} alt control S
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Control via the exchange:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}Activate/deacticate hotkey passing.
@{par}@{"Show" link A_open} or @{"Hide" link A_close} the configuration window.
@{par}@{"Remove" link A_quit} mrjQuote.
@{par}
@{par}Note that no commodity events can be processed whilst a quote/file/font
requester is open, although they should be queued.
@{par}
@endnode
@node ARexx "mrjQuote ; Use of ARexx"
@{par}@{b}Use of ARexx@{ub}
@{par}~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{par}  Under Workbench 2 or above, mrjQuote can open an ARexx port which will allow
you to have a large amount of control over the program via ARexx, either
directly or using other programs. To utilise ARexx, you'll need to have the
program RexxMast either in you WBStartub drawer or user-startup script. By
default, the ARexx port is called "QUOTE".  This can be changed via the
@{"configuration" link Configuration}, but note that this change will not take effect until mrjQuote
quit and restarted (assuming that this change has been saved), and will entail
manual alteration of any ARexx scripts other than mrjQuote macros.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}List of ARexx commands:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}Note that there have been changes since v2.20. (Get and Set have replaced
some older commands.) All commands are case-insensitive.
@{par}
@{par}@{" Quote  [<QuoteList>]           " link A_quote}
@{par}@{" Reply  [<QuoteList>]           " link A_reply}
@{par}@{" Sig    [<SigList>]             " link A_sig}
@{par}@{" Open                           " link A_open}
@{par}@{" Close                          " link A_close}
@{par}@{" Use                            " link A_use}
@{par}@{" Save                           " link A_save}
@{par}@{" SaveAs [<PrefsFile>]           " link A_saveas}
@{par}@{" Load   [<PrefsFile>]           " link A_load}
@{par}@{" Cancel                         " link A_cancel}
@{par}@{" Quit                           " link A_quit}
@{par}@{" Get    <Variable>              " link A_getset}
@{par}@{" Set    <Variable> [<FileName>] " link A_getset}
@{par}@{" Macro  [<MacroName>]           " link A_macro}
@{par}
@{par}  Most of the commands perform the same function as gadgets/menus of the
@{"configuration window" link Configuration} with similar names, albeit with the option to supply
filenames directly rather than popping up a file requester.
@{par}  Reply can be used to get quotes in a format suitable for further processing
by an ARexx script, and Get & Set allow you to find and/or change some of the
filenames used by mrjQuote.
@{par}  Note that setting RESULT from Blitz 2 programs doesn't seem to work, so the
value that should be in RESULT is also stored in the file T:mrjQuote. See the
supplied ARexx scripts for examples of usage.
@{par}  Note also that the ARexx port is frozen whilst any requester is open.
Commands will, however, be queued and executed once the requester is closed.
@{par}  ARexx commands will be replised to only when the operation they cause is
completed (eg after a file is created or a file requester closed), with the
exception of 'Quote' which will reply immediately and 'Macro' which will
reply once the execution request is sent to ARexx.
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Errors processing ARexx commands:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}If an error occurs during the processing of an ARexx command, RC will be set
to one of the following values:
@{par}
@{par}@{b}10@{ub} - No such command
@{par}@{b}11@{ub} - Unable to open file
@{par}@{b}12@{ub} - No such variable           (Get/Set)
@{par}@{b}13@{ub} - Unable to open T:mrjQuote  (Reply/Get)
@{par}
@{par}@{b}Supplied ARexx scripts:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}@{" mrjQuote.rexx    " link Rexx} - CLI replacement for using Quote directly
@{par}@{" mrjQuote.dopus5  " link DOpus5} - ARexx Module for Directory Opus 5.5
@{par}@{" IndentAddSig.ged " link Editor} - GoldEd 4 macro for use with email etc
@{par}@{" IndentAddSig.bed " link Editor} - Blacks Editor macro for use with email etc
@{par}
@{par}  Don't forget to read the documentation contained in the scripts themselves
and carry out any neccessary configuration before use.
@{par}
@endnode
@node More "mrjQuote : Adding More or Different Quotes"
@{par}@{b}Adding More or Different Quotes@{ub}
@{par}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{par}  mrjQuote gets it's quotes from a QuoteList file.  See @{"configuration" link Configuration} for
how to specify which QuoteList is used.  This QuoteList can be in either of
the two formats below:
@{par}
@{par}@{b}List of Quotes:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}  This is the basic file, containing the actual quotes. The first line gives
the number of quotes in the file. The remainder of the file is the quotes,
each one preceeded by a line starting with two percent characters '%%'.
@{par}                   
@{par}@{b}List of QuoteLists:@{ub}
@{par}
@{par}  More advanced, this alows you to split your quote collection over several
smaller files, speeding up access times. The first line gives the number of
QuoteLists referred to.  Each line in the remainder of the file can reference
either a QuoteList or a directory. A reference to a QuoteList can either give
a full path, including device (ie containing a ':'), or a relative path (most
usually just the filename itself) from the current directory. The current
directory is initially the directory in which the file be parsed resides, but
any line which refers to a directory (this @{b}must@{ub} end in a trailing /
or :) will change the current directory for future QuoteLists. If a relative
directory is given, this is relative to the directory in which the file be
parsed is, @{b}not@{ub} the current directory.
@{par}
@{par}  Take a look at the quote files suppplied for a better idea. The basic
file format is the same as several other quote or fortune generators, which
should make it easier to find new quotes. I'll try to keep a reasonably
up-to-date (with UK showings) set of Babylon 5 quote files on my B5 Web page:
http://users.ox.ac.uk/~kebl0206/babylon5/
@{par}
@endnode
@node Babylon5 "mrjQuote : Babylon 5 Episode List"
@{par}@{b}Babylon 5 Episode List@{ub}
@{par}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
@{par}  Babylon 5 is a space science-fiction television series set over five years
between 2257 and 2262 based on a space station of the same name, which serves
as a neutral meeting place for both humans and many alien races. What sets B5
apart from its competitors is the pre-planned five year storyline, a gritty
realism, and the way that major characters, places, governments and even whole
alien races can come and go.
@{par}  The Babylon 5 Quotes supplied with mrjQuote are organised on an episode-by-
episode basis. Note that there are not quote files for every one of the
episodes listed yet (at the time of writing, only the first three seasons have
been screened and I haven't got quotes for all of them yet).
@{par}
@{par}For more information on Babylon 5, I can recommend The Lurkers' Guide to
Babylon 5: http://www.hyperion.com/lurk/lurker.html  For more information on
an individual episode, for the quotefile xxx.txt, look at the Lurkers' Guide
page http://www.hyperion.com/lurk/guide/xxx.html
@{par}
@{par} @{" Pilot Movie   " link Pilot} "The Gathering"
@{par} @{" First Season  " link Season1} "Signs and Portents"
@{par} @{" Second Season " link Season2} "The Coming of Shadows"
@{par} @{" Third Season  " link Season3} "Point of No Return"
@{par} @{" Fourth Season " link Season4}
@{par} @{" Final Season  " link Season5}
@{par}
@endnode
